recalls.Summary: BMW of North America, LLC (BMW) is recalling certain 2008-2012 BMW 128i, 135i, 135is Coupes and 128i, 135i Convertible vehicles.  The wiring and electrical connectors in the blower-regulator wiring harness may overheat.
recalls.Consequence: Wiring that overheats could cause the electrical connectors to melt, and increase the risk of a fire, even when the vehicle is unattended.
recalls.Remedy: BMW will notify owners, and dealers will inspect the blower-regulator wiring harness, and replace it with a new part, free of charge.  The recall began October 4, 2019.  Owners may contact BMW customer service at 1-800-525-7417.  Note:  This recall is an expansion of an earlier recall number 17V-676.
recalls.Notes: Owners may also contact the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration Vehicle Safety Hotline at 1-888-327-4236 (TTY 1-800-424-9153), or go to www.safercar.gov.

recalls.Summary:
BMW of North America, LLC (BMW) is recalling certain 2008-2013 128i and 135i Convertibles, 128i, 135i, and M Coupes, 2007-2010 X3 30si and X3 xDrive30i, 2013-2015 X1 sDrive28i, X1 xDrive28i and X1 xDrive35i, 2007-2013 328i, 328i xDrive, 335i, 335is, 335i xDrive and M3 Coupes, 2006-2011 328i, 328xi, 328i xDrive, 325i, 325xi, 330i, 330xi, 335i, 335xi, 335i
xDrive and M3, 2009-2011 335D, 2006-2012 325xi, 328i, 328xi and 328i xDrive, 2010-2011 X6 ActiveHybrid, 2007-2013 328i, 335i, 335is, M3 Coupes, X5 30si, X5 xDrive30i, X5 xDrive35i, X5 48i, X5 xDrive48i, X5 xDrive50i and X5 M, 2009-2013 X5 xDrive35d and 2008-2014 X6 xDrive35i, X6 xDrive50i and X6M vehicles equipped with non-desiccated driver frontal air bag inflators containing phase stabilized ammonium nitrate (PSAN) that were used as interim remedy parts for previous Takata recalls.  These inflators may explode due to propellant degradation occurring after long-term exposure to high absolute humidity, high temperatures, and high temperature cycling.
recalls.Consequence: An inflator explosion may result in sharp metal fragments striking the driver or other occupants resulting in serious injury or death.
recalls.Remedy: BMW will notify owners, and dealers will replace the driver air bag.  On X5 and X6 vehicles, only the inflator will be replaced.  All repairs will be performed free of charge.  The recall began March 11, 2020.  Owners may contact BMW customer service at 1-800-525-7417.
recalls.Notes: Owners may also contact the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration Vehicle Safety Hotline at 1-888-327-4236 (TTY 1-800-424-9153), or go to www.safercar.gov.

recalls.Summary: BMW of North America, LLC (BMW) is recalling certain model year 2008-2013 128i and 135i coupes and convertibles and 1 Series M coupes, 2006-2011 325i, 325xi, 328i, 328xi, 328i xDrive, 330i, 330xi, 335i, 335xi, 335i xDrive Sedans, 2009-2011 335d sedans, 2006-2012 325xiT, 328i and 328xi sports wagons, 2007-2013 328i, 328xi, 328i xDrive, 335i, 335xi, 335i xDrive, 335is and M3 Coupes and Convertibles, 2013-2015 X1 sDrive28i, X1 xDrive28i and X1 xDrive35i SAVs, 2007-2010 X3 xDrive30i SAVs, 2007-2013 X5 xDrive30i, X5 xDrive35i, X5 xDrive48i, X5 xDrive50i and X5 M SAVs, 2009-2013 BMW X5 xDrive35d SAVs, 2008-2014 X6 xDrive35i, X6 xDrive50i, and X6 M SACs, 2010-2011 BMW X6 xDrive50i SACs and 2008-2011 M3 Sedan vehicles.  Upon deployment of the driver's frontal air bag, excessive internal pressure may cause the inflator to rupture.
recalls.Consequence: In the event of a crash necessitating deployment of the driver's frontal air bag, the inflator could rupture with metal fragments striking the driver or other occupants resulting in serious injury or death.
recalls.Remedy: BMW will notify owners, and dealers will replace the driver's frontal air bag module or inflator depending on the vehicle model, free of charge.  The recall began March 9, 2018.  Owners may contact BMW customer service at 1-800-525-7417.
recalls.Notes: Owners may also contact the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration Vehicle Safety Hotline at 1-888-327-4236 (TTY 1-800-424-9153), or go to www.safercar.gov.

recalls.Summary: BMW is recalling certain model year 2008-2012 1-Series coupes and convertibles manufactured December 2007 through September 2011; and 2007-2011 3-Series coupes and convertibles manufactured March 2007 through October 2011; 2007-2011 3-Series sedans manufactured March 2007 through October 2011; 2007-2011 3-Series sports wagons manufactured March 2007 through June 2011; and 2009-2011 Z4 vehicles manufactured March 2009 through June 2011.  In February 2013, BMW recalled 504,545 vehicles.  In July 2013, BMW informed the agency that it was adding 1-Series, 3-Series, and Z4 vehicles, representing an additional 12,094 vehicles.  The total number of vehicles being recalled is now 516,791.  The connector for the positive battery cable connector and the corresponding terminal on the fuse box may degrade over time.  Over time, the high current flow and heat from electrical resistance may lead to a breakage of the connection, and a loss of electrical power to the vehicle.
recalls.Consequence: If there is a loss of electrical power to the vehicle, the vehicle may unexpectedly stall, increasing the risk of a crash.
recalls.Remedy: BMW will notify owners, and dealers will replace the positive battery cable connector and secure it with an improved method, free of charge.  The recall began on March 13, 2013.  Owners may call BMW at 1-800-525-7417 or email BMW at CustomerRelations@bmwusa.com.
recalls.Notes: Owners may also contact the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration Vehicle Safety Hotline at 1-888-327-4236 (TTY 1-800-424-9153), or go to www.safercar.gov.

issues.title: High Pressure Fuel Pump (HPFP) Failure
issues.description: The high pressure fuel pump commonly fails on N54 engines, causing fuel starvation and potential engine damage. This is one of the most documented issues with the N54 platform.
issues.fix_description: Replace high pressure fuel pump with updated revision. BMW issued multiple revisions to address this problem.
issues.prevention: Use high quality fuel, replace fuel filter regularly, avoid running fuel tank very low

issues.title: Carbon Buildup on Intake Valves
issues.description: Direct injection N54 engines suffer from carbon buildup on intake valves due to lack of port injection to clean valves. This reduces performance and can cause misfires.
issues.fix_description: Walnut blast cleaning of intake valves every 60,000-80,000 miles. Some opt for catch can installation.
issues.prevention: Install oil catch can, use top tier gasoline, occasional Italian tune-up (high RPM driving)

issues.title: Wastegate Rattle
issues.description: The wastegate arms on the turbochargers develop play and rattle, especially at idle. This is a common issue that affects both turbos.
issues.fix_description: Replace turbochargers or have wastegates rebuilt. Some aftermarket solutions available for welding wastegate shut.
issues.prevention: Regular oil changes, allow turbo cooldown, avoid aggressive driving when engine is cold

issues.title: Injector Failure
issues.description: Direct injection fuel injectors commonly fail on N54 engines, causing rough running, misfires, and potential engine damage from running lean.
issues.fix_description: Replace failed injectors. BMW has issued updated injector revisions. Often multiple injectors fail over time.
issues.prevention: Use high quality fuel, fuel system cleaners, regular maintenance

issues.title: Water Pump Failure
issues.description: Electric water pump failure is common, leading to overheating and potential engine damage. The plastic impeller commonly breaks.
issues.fix_description: Replace water pump and thermostat. Often done as preventive maintenance with other cooling system components.
issues.prevention: Regular coolant changes, monitor coolant levels, replace thermostat proactively

issues.title: Oil Filter Housing Gasket Leak
issues.description: The oil filter housing gasket commonly fails, causing oil leaks onto the exhaust manifold and creating burning oil smell.
issues.fix_description: Replace oil filter housing gasket and oil cooler seals. Common maintenance item that should be addressed promptly.
issues.prevention: Regular oil changes, inspect for leaks during maintenance

issues.title: Ignition Coil Failure
issues.description: Ignition coils commonly fail on N54 engines, causing misfires and rough running. The high boost environment stresses the coils.
issues.fix_description: Replace failed ignition coils and spark plugs. BMW issued updated coil revisions. Often replace all 6 coils together.
issues.prevention: Use OEM or high quality coils, replace spark plugs at recommended intervals

issues.title: Charge Pipe Failure
issues.description: The plastic charge pipe from the turbo to the intercooler commonly cracks or the connection fails, causing boost leaks and reduced performance.
issues.fix_description: Replace with upgraded aluminum charge pipe or reinforce OEM pipe. Check all boost pipe connections.
issues.prevention: Inspect boost pipes regularly, avoid excessive boost modifications without supporting upgrades

issues.title: Valve Cover Gasket Leak
issues.description: Valve cover gasket commonly develops leaks, causing oil seepage and potential ignition coil contamination.
issues.fix_description: Replace valve cover gasket and clean oil from ignition coils. Good time to replace coils if contaminated.
issues.prevention: Regular inspection during oil changes, address leaks promptly

issues.title: Turbo Oil Lines Leaking
issues.description: Oil feed and return lines to the turbochargers commonly develop leaks, starving turbos of oil and causing potential failure.
issues.fix_description: Replace turbo oil feed and return lines. Often done when doing other turbo maintenance.
issues.prevention: Regular oil changes, check for leaks during maintenance, use correct oil viscosity

issues.title: PCV Valve and Breather Hoses
issues.description: PCV system components including valve and hoses commonly fail, causing rough idle and oil consumption issues.
issues.fix_description: Replace PCV valve, oil separator, and associated breather hoses. Part of regular maintenance schedule.
issues.prevention: Regular maintenance intervals, use quality oil, monitor for vacuum leaks

issues.title: Intercooler Heat Soak
issues.description: Factory intercooler suffers from heat soak in traffic or hot weather, reducing performance and increasing likelihood of knock.
issues.fix_description: Upgrade to larger aftermarket intercooler for improved heat dissipation and consistent performance.
issues.prevention: Allow cooldown periods, avoid aggressive driving in hot weather, consider intercooler upgrade

editorial.tagline: Twin-turbo fury in a compact package
editorial.hero_blurb: The BMW 135i N54 represents the sweet spot of BMW's 1-Series lineup, packing serious turbocharged punch into a lightweight, rear-wheel-drive chassis. This is the enthusiast's choice for those who want M3 performance without the M3 price tag.
editorial.essence: The 135i N54 is BMW's answer to the hot hatch phenomenon, but with rear-wheel drive and proper German engineering. It's a wolf in sheep's clothing that can embarrass much more expensive sports cars while still being practical enough for daily duty.
editorial.heritage: Born from BMW's desire to create an affordable entry point into their performance lineup, the 135i carried on the tradition of the iconic 2002 turbo with modern twin-turbo technology and the legendary N54 engine that would power everything from the 335i to the Z4.
editorial.design_philosophy: Clean, understated lines that prioritize function over flash, with subtle aerodynamic enhancements and a purposeful stance that hints at the performance potential lurking beneath the conservative exterior styling.
editorial.motorsport_history: While not factory-raced extensively, the 135i became a favorite in grassroots motorsport and time attack events, with its potent N54 engine and balanced chassis proving highly competitive in modified form.
editorial.engine_character: The N54 twin-turbo delivers immediate, linear power with virtually no turbo lag, building torque from just 1,500 RPM and maintaining strong pull all the way to redline with a satisfying mechanical growl.
editorial.transmission_feel: The 6-speed manual offers precise, notchy shifts with well-defined gates, while the optional automatic provides quick, decisive shifts that complement the engine's broad torque band perfectly.
editorial.chassis_dynamics: Near-perfect 50/50 weight distribution creates neutral handling with predictable oversteer characteristics, while the compact wheelbase makes it incredibly agile and responsive in tight corners.
editorial.steering_feel: Hydraulic power steering provides excellent feedback and proper weight, with quick ratio that makes the car feel nimble without being twitchy, maintaining BMW's reputation for steering excellence.
editorial.brake_confidence: Strong, progressive brakes with excellent pedal feel and fade resistance, providing confident stopping power that matches the engine's performance capabilities.
editorial.sound_signature: A distinctive twin-turbo whoosh under acceleration paired with a sophisticated inline-six rumble, creating an addictive soundtrack that's refined yet purposeful.
editorial.ideal_owner: Driving enthusiasts who want genuine sports car performance in a practical package, those who appreciate understated looks over flashy styling, and anyone seeking a reliable performance car with strong aftermarket support.
editorial.not_ideal_for: Buyers seeking luxury amenities, those wanting flashy styling to announce their performance intentions, or anyone afraid of potential high-pressure fuel pump issues requiring preventive maintenance.
editorial.buyers_summary: Look for well-maintained examples with documented HPFP replacements and avoid heavily modified cars unless you're prepared for project status. The N54 engine responds incredibly well to modifications but requires knowledgeable maintenance.

expertReviews.title: My HONEST BMW N54 Powered 135i 1 Year Ownership ...
pros: Perfect combination between E46 and E92
Makes around 500 wheel horsepower with upgrades
cons: Initial setup required extensive work and sourcing parts
VANOS solenoid failure within first month
Can be expensive to maintain properly
Not true M car handling without major suspension work
expertReviews.verdict: Owner gives 10/10 rating after 1 year and 5,000 miles of ownership. Despite initial challenges including engine rebuild and various component failures, the 135i has been flawless after proper maintenance. The car offers exceptional driving experience with lightweight chassis, strong N54 performance, and successful 1M clone conversion. Emphasizes that N54 reliability depends heavily on proper maintenance and previous owner care.

expertReviews.title: BMW 135i N54 500 BHP *Ultimate Review*
pros: Huge tuning potential up to 800+ horsepower
Strong Brembo brakes with good initial bite
Livable on street with aftermarket suspension
cons: Needs to be manhandled to get best performance
expertReviews.verdict: The BMW 135i N54 is a tuner's dream with massive potential reaching 500+ horsepower easily and up to 800+ with serious modifications. While it has significant chassis issues from factory (poor rear end, understeer, damping), these can be fixed with E90 M3 parts and aftermarket suspension. At under $20k for good examples, it offers supercar-killing performance potential but requires substantial modifications to handle properly.

expertReviews.title: I bought the best BMW made in the last decade (with the ...)
expertReviews.verdict: The reviewer considers this the best BMW made in the last decade due to its size, handling, and tunability, but acknowledges the N54 engine's terrible reliability makes it a problematic ownership experience. Despite the car's excellent driving dynamics, the constant mechanical issues make it difficult to recommend.

expertReviews.title: The Best BMW M Car We Never Got! | BMW E82 135i Review
pros: Same N55 engine as first generation M2 with 306hp
Six piston brake calipers (better than M2/1M)
Hydraulic steering system provides pure feel
Underrated and rare - flies under the radar
Proper BMW driving dynamics and feel
cons: No limited slip differential from factory
Needs exhaust modification to sound better
Front end feels slightly light in corners
Some body lean in stock suspension setup
DCT can be sluggish in automatic mode
N54 early models less reliable than N55
expertReviews.verdict: The BMW 135i is described as the greatest non-M car the reviewer has driven and a hidden gem. With the N55 engine, DCT transmission, and excellent brakes, it offers M-car performance for a fraction of the price. The reviewer considers it a future classic and plans to buy one, praising its old-school BMW feel, perfect proportions, and engaging driving experience. At 10,000, it's exceptional value for money.

expertReviews.title: This 600hp BMW 135i Shows Why the N54 is the Euro 2JZ
pros: Maintains BMW's excellent balance and handling characteristics
Can switch between normal driving and attack mode seamlessly
Excellent hydraulic steering and rear-wheel drive dynamics
Great build quality interior with perfect ergonomics
Modifications make it both faster and more reliable
Easy to rev match and enjoyable manual gearbox
cons: Long gear ratios limit fun factor in lower gears
First and second gear struggle to put power down
Wooden interior trim instead of preferred silver
N54 engine known for reliability issues in stock form
Expensive fuel injectors and turbo maintenance
expertReviews.verdict: This heavily modified 135i with 440kW (600hp) demonstrates the N54's incredible potential when properly tuned. Despite initial reservations about the stock 135i's laggy throttle and long gears, this build transforms it into a sensational drive that's both brutally fast and remarkably controllable. The modifications address reliability concerns while doubling factory power, creating a car that can be docile in sixth gear or devastating in third. The reviewer was smiling the entire time - high praise for what he calls a 'faultless execution' of nearly 600hp in a compact, rear-wheel drive coupe.
